00:56:25,840 --> 00:56:32,960
next corner of the diamond, what do you have to 
win? Write that down. On the bottom, what do you  

535
00:56:32,960 --> 00:56:42,000
need to win? And then on that final angle on the 
left-hand side, what do you have to say to win?"  

536
00:56:43,280 --> 00:56:49,520
Then I said, "Now, let's go all the way to that 
final thing of what do you have to say to win."
 

537
00:56:49,520 --> 00:56:54,560
And that's where you just get people thinking 
about, "Well, what we really have here is...  

538
00:56:54,560 --> 00:57:01,440
And we're better than this." And then I'll just 
say, "Okay. Now, what you want to take that this  

539
00:57:01,440 --> 00:57:07,840
really should be about experience and behavior. 
How do you want to behave in the marketplace? How  

540
00:57:07,840 --> 00:57:16,080
do you want the marketplace to behave towards you? 
And what kind of experience are you creating?" And  

541
00:57:16,080 --> 00:57:20,960
then they'll start talking a little bit. I'll 
say, "Now, you just need to probe on that. You  

542
00:57:20,960 --> 00:57:27,440
need to keep going. You need to look at metaphors 
because this is about experience." And I'll just  

543
00:57:27,440 --> 00:57:34,800
give them some of our examples that we've talked 
about, "Blackberry, it says to the marketplace,  

544
00:57:34,800 --> 00:57:42,240
they're not like the other guys." Think 
of something like Google versus Infoseek,  

545
00:57:42,240 --> 00:57:47,360
right? Google is an experience. Google says, 
"I don't know what these guys are going to do,  

546
00:57:47,360 --> 00:57:54,080
but it's not this practical mundane 
Infoseek." And that's what attracts people.
 

547
00:57:54,080 --> 00:58:00,640
And so I'll do a little coaching like that, 
and then that usually kind of sets them free.  

548
00:58:00,640 --> 00:58:08,000
And they're now thinking about it not as 
a word, which has maybe limited value,  

549
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:12,720
but as creating an experience which has 
the potential for unlimited value.
 

550
00:58:12,720 --> 00:58:18,080
Okay. So, let me try to reflect this back for 
folks. So the advice is draw triangle. So, you're  

551
00:58:18,080 --> 00:58:24,960
coming up with a name. Draw triangle. At the top, 
win. At the bottom-left, was it how do you win?
 

552
00:58:24,960 --> 00:58:30,400
Yeah. So, the diamond is two triangles.
Oh, diamond. Okay, I see. I have triangle in my  

553
00:58:30,400 --> 00:58:30,640
mind.
I got you.
 

554
00:58:30,640 --> 00:58:34,560
Okay, got it. Diamond. Great.
And so on that next angle there  

555
00:58:34,560 --> 00:58:40,320
on the right side is, what do you have to win 
already? Right? Because they wouldn't be either  

556
00:58:40,320 --> 00:58:48,800
in a Y Combinator or getting some seed money if 
they didn't have something to win. And often,  

557
00:58:48,800 --> 00:58:53,520
people, startups don't appreciate how much 
they actually do have to win because they're  

558
00:58:53,520 --> 00:59:01,440
so busy and so stressed on what they're doing. And 
then, what do they need to win? And then finally,  

559
00:59:01,440 --> 00:59:08,720
what do you need to say? And then back up 
to defining what is winning to us? Which,  

560
00:59:08,720 --> 00:59:15,040
by the way, we start with that question 
usually on an assignment that we've been  

561
00:59:15,040 --> 00:59:19,680
awarded. And if we're in a room with five 
people, all five people have a different  

562
00:59:21,040 --> 00:59:26,640
definition of what... Their definition of that 
company winning. And that's good to sort that  

563
00:59:26,640 --> 00:59:31,440
out because we can move down different 
avenues from a creative standpoint.
 

564
00:59:31,440 --> 00:59:34,400
Let's just make sure people have these 
phrases because this is awesome. And I  

565
00:59:34,400 --> 00:59:37,520
imagine many people are going to be taking 
notes and like, "Cool. I'm going to do this."  

566
00:59:37,520 --> 00:59:42,400
I hope so say the four points of the diamond 
again just so folks can write it all down.
 

567
00:59:42,400 --> 00:59:49,040
At the top of the diamond is just the word win, 
and underneath that is how do we define winning  

568
00:59:49,040 --> 00:59:55,760
for us as a company. And that can start off being 
simple, like we want to be the dominant player  

569
00:59:55,760 --> 01:00:02,320
here. But you really have to work at that. What 
does that really mean, right? The second on that  

570
01:00:02,320 --> 01:00:08,880
right-hand tip there of the diamond is what do we 
have to win? What are we doing now that makes us  

571
01:00:08,880 --> 01:00:16,640
a winner? Then we go down to the bottom of the 
diamond, and it's what do we need to win? There  

572
01:00:16,640 --> 01:00:23,360
could be technical things there. People talk about 
talent and resources. Often there, they'll say,  

573
01:00:23,360 --> 01:00:28,240
"We need a good name." We always correct that. 
It's not the good name, it's the right name.
 

574
01:00:28,240 --> 01:00:31,360
And then finally is what do we need 
to say? And that's where I say,  

575
01:00:31,360 --> 01:00:37,680
that's where you want to spend some time in really 
thinking about all the things you need to say,  

576
01:00:37,680 --> 01:00:43,760
that you can say or you would even like to say, 
which maybe right now you can't say. But you  

577
01:00:43,760 --> 01:00:48,720
want to a name that actually is going to have 
the flexibility as to when you can say that,  

578
01:00:48,720 --> 01:00:55,280
it still works. And that gets them into behavior 
and experience. And that usually launches a really  

579
01:00:57,200 --> 01:01:04,640
a good discussion with founders internally.
When you say you have to win though,  

580
01:01:04,640 --> 01:01:08,560
what you're thinking about there is what is it 
that you have that will help you win? And then  

581
01:01:08,560 --> 01:01:11,680
what is it you need to have this win?
Yes, that's right. And all companies are  

582
01:01:11,680 --> 01:01:15,200
in that same situation. They have 
a bunch of stuff, but they need...  

583
01:01:16,160 --> 01:01:22,800
A P&G might say, "We need a good distributor."
"Okay. All right, we'll put that on the list."
 

584
01:01:22,800 --> 01:01:27,840
And then you might say, "Well, we need in..." 
When it gets to what do we have to say, we have  

585
01:01:27,840 --> 01:01:35,280
to say the right things so that a distributor is 
interested in us. And then you go down an avenue  

586
01:01:35,280 --> 01:01:45,280
there. Well, what is that? And if you work at 
it, this is not a one-hour exercise, it may be an  

587
01:01:45,280 --> 01:01:50,960
exercise repeated over the next 4 or 5 days.
Okay. So, you have this diamond. And then  

588
01:01:50,960 --> 01:01:55,840
the idea is just sit and put names 
down in a Google Doc, let's say.
 

589
01:01:55,840 --> 01:02:04,560
Yeah. And then you start. But there is 
this... And maybe, it's naivete. I guess,  

590
01:02:04,560 --> 01:02:09,600
that's probably the best word for this is that, 
because I do hear this all of the time. "Hey,  

591
01:02:10,400 --> 01:02:19,840
we've worked at this, we got a list of 200 names, 
but we don't think there's something there."
 

592
01:02:19,840 --> 01:02:28,720
And I'll say, "Well, 200 names is not enough. 
Get to 1,000, 1,500 names and directions.  

593
01:02:28,720 --> 01:02:36,480
Don't evaluate them. Just generate names, and 
directions, and ideas, and then have a meeting.  

594
01:02:36,480 --> 01:02:43,920
And don't evaluate but speculate." What could 
we do with this name? What's the potential here?  

595
01:02:46,240 --> 01:02:57,680
There's a lot of overevaluation in our industry. 
It makes sense. We survive as humans because we  

596
01:02:57,680 --> 01:03:04,720
figure out what's wrong with this picture. If I 
want to cross the street, is it safe to cross the  

597
01:03:04,720 --> 01:03:09,200
street? What's going on? Those kinds of things. 
You have to counter that. You have to say, "Let's  

598
01:03:09,200 --> 01:03:15,840
just suspend judgment for a while. And let's do 
an exercise here where we take these 10 names  

599
01:03:15,840 --> 01:03:20,640
that we think might work and what are we going 
to do with it." Because it's how you execute.
 

600
01:03:21,600 --> 01:03:28,400
Going back to windsurf, as we showed them pictures 
of people windsurfing and waves and things, if  

601
01:03:28,400 --> 01:03:33,040
they said, "Ah, that just doesn't work for us at 
all. I'm very uncomfortable with." Well, then it's  

602
01:03:33,040 --> 01:03:42,160
not their name. But they leaned into it, "Okay, 
I can see this. It's easy for us to execute. It's  

603
01:03:42,160 --> 01:03:50,720
dynamic, it's different." So, that's why we build 
these prototypes for people. And that's what... I  

604
01:03:50,720 --> 01:03:56,240
think the best advice I can give to whether it's a 
startup or someone starting a new cookie company,  

605
01:03:56,240 --> 01:04:06,000
is it's not just a list of 200 names. It's 10 or 
15 lists of 200 names. And it's thinking about  

606
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:11,120
what do we have to say here? What behavior? How 
do we want people to feel in the marketplace about  

607
01:04:11,120 --> 01:04:18,080
us? I imagine with Google, people felt relief 
that it wasn't a descriptive name. That there  

608
01:04:18,080 --> 01:04:22,640
was something new out there in the marketplace.
Yeah. Infoseek, that's such a descriptive name now  

609
01:04:22,640 --> 01:04:24,000
that I think about it.
Yes.
 

610
01:04:24,000 --> 01:04:28,160
Okay, so one more question along these lines. So 
say, you have a list of let's say 2,000 or 1,000  

611
01:04:28,720 --> 01:04:34,720
names. There's this tension between choosing 
something... Like, as a person that is doing  

612
01:04:34,720 --> 01:04:39,840
them themselves. Your advice is choose something 
bold, not something descriptive. You won't know  

613
01:04:39,840 --> 01:04:45,040
it when you see it. Very hard to do, obviously, 
when you're doing it by yourself. And you just  

614
01:04:45,040 --> 01:04:52,640
advise for not losing sight of that piece. Just 
throwing out things that feel too scary, finding  

615
01:04:52,640 --> 01:05:00,880
a name that's actually bold as you suggest.
First off, we disappear... Human psychology,  

616
01:05:01,440 --> 01:05:08,000
humans only pay attention to what is new or what 
is different, I should say. So if you're looking  

617
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:12,800
at shoes and they're all black, black, black, 
black, and then the next pair of shoes is red,  

618
01:05:12,800 --> 01:05:17,520
that's the first thing you focus on. And so, that 
usually gives people permission. They'll say,  

619
01:05:17,520 --> 01:05:25,920
"Okay, I get that." So, look for what is really 
different between the names that you have on your  

620
01:05:25,920 --> 01:05:33,840
list, but also what's different from what's out 
in the marketplace. Then you get a client like  

621
01:05:33,840 --> 01:05:41,040
Microsoft saying, "Azure is different. There's 
going to be a lot of cloud stuff and..." There's  

622
01:05:41,040 --> 01:05:49,680
a relevant point there, Azure is blue. And so, 
there's a slight logical connection that I think  

623
01:05:49,680 --> 01:05:57,840
gave them more permission to move forward with it, 
frankly. But listen, this is not an easy task. I  

624
01:05:57,840 --> 01:06:05,120
mean, that's why we're in this business, and why 
I felt we should be specialized because if you  

625
01:06:05,120 --> 01:06:16,640
start doing design and/or advertising or other 
things, you can't have the intellectual engine.
 

626
01:06:16,640 --> 01:06:22,480
You can't acquire the intellectual engine that 
we have. So I know it's difficult, but it can  

627
01:06:22,480 --> 01:06:29,840
be done, and you just have to give yourself some 
time. But stop evaluating. Suspend judgment and  

628
01:06:29,840 --> 01:06:38,160
speculate. That's my number one advice to people 
trying to do this on their own. Now, how can you  

629
01:06:38,160 --> 01:06:46,160
get help? You can talk to your employees, but 
it's not so much, "What do you think of this  

630
01:06:46,160 --> 01:06:52,320
name?" It's, "What do you think this name could 
do for us?" That's a much better question. If  

631
01:06:52,320 --> 01:07:01,200
you go out and talk to friends who don't work for 
your company, there's a fun drill that I suggest.  

632
01:07:01,200 --> 01:07:05,600
I said, "Listen, go out to them and say..." 
They'll know what you're doing. And say, "You  

633
01:07:05,600 --> 01:07:10,640
know what? We just have a new competitor and their 
name is blank. What do you think about that?"
 

634
01:07:10,640 --> 01:07:16,960
What happens there is you're not asking them 
to give you an opinion to evaluate a name.  

635
01:07:16,960 --> 01:07:22,640
You're asking them then what does that name do for 
you? The information you're getting is that name,  

636
01:07:22,640 --> 01:07:28,720
they're telling you what that name does for 
them, how it helps them to imagine, which is  

637
01:07:28,720 --> 01:07:37,360
a fundamental role of any name. Slight tangent, 
but I'm going to go to our kind of research. We do  

638
01:07:37,360 --> 01:07:46,800
mostly quantitative research now, but for years, 
we did qualitative work. And we still do. But what  

639
01:07:46,800 --> 01:07:51,120
we found in, we were always looking for the...
I'll set it this way. We were always looking for  

640
01:07:51,120 --> 01:07:58,080
this answer from consumers. If a consumer said, 
"I don't really know much about that new product,  

641
01:07:58,080 --> 01:08:05,040
but I know that they're not like the other 
guys." That's when we knew we had a good name  

642
01:08:06,480 --> 01:08:11,920
because they were... Now what happened there? 
I mean, the technical term that we use is that  

643
01:08:11,920 --> 01:08:18,720
name will create a predisposition to consider this 
product because they're not like the other guys,  

644
01:08:18,720 --> 01:08:23,920
as opposed to, "I already have something 
like that. I'm busy. I don't need another  

645
01:08:23,920 --> 01:08:30,400
one of those things. I need something new 
and different, and hopefully better."
 

646
01:08:30,400 --> 01:08:34,240
That's awesome. That's a good reminder. There's a 
quote that I found of yours that's exactly along  

647
01:08:34,240 --> 01:08:38,720
these lines, "If your team is comfortable with the 
name, chances are you don't have the name yet."
 

648
01:08:38,720 --> 01:08:47,760
Yes. And by the way, the opposite of that is we 
look for polarization. We look for tension in a  

649
01:08:47,760 --> 01:08:56,320
team about arguing about these things, because we 
think that polarization is a sign of strength in  

650
01:08:56,320 --> 01:09:05,440
the word. And interesting story, the person who 
taught me that, honestly, was Andy Grove over the  

651
01:09:05,440 --> 01:09:14,080
Pentium name, because... And I learned a lot from 
him. I always say this, I just was very fortunate  

652
01:09:14,800 --> 01:09:24,800
to work with him on Pentium, and Xeon, and a few 
other things. But when we went to an executive  

653
01:09:24,800 --> 01:09:32,720
committee to present Pentium... And by the way, 
internally, one of the names that... And makes  

654
01:09:32,720 --> 01:09:40,560
sense here, descriptive, bunch of engineers, 
ProChip. "Hey, it's professional, it's premium,  

655
01:09:40,560 --> 01:09:49,600
and it's chipped. So, it should be Prochip." 
So Andy had me give a presentation about the  

656
01:09:49,600 --> 01:09:56,720
strengths of this thing, and he said, "Now, let 
me tell you why I think this is the right name."
 

657
01:09:56,720 --> 01:10:03,280
He said, "Because I see the polarization here in 
it amongst people. There's this ProChip over here,  

658
01:10:03,280 --> 01:10:08,720
there's the Pentium thing." He said, "That tells 
me there's energy for Pentium here." And he said,  

659
01:10:08,720 --> 01:10:12,480
"That's why I think we should go with it." 
And I've never forgotten that. And so,  

660
01:10:12,480 --> 01:10:17,920
we do look for that. And when we tell that story, 
people say, "You're right. There is... I mean,  

661
01:10:17,920 --> 01:10:22,800
we are arguing about this, and there is an 
intensity with the name." And that's what you  

662
01:10:22,800 --> 01:10:27,760
want. You don't want to go out in the marketplace, 
into this very competitive marketplace,  

663
01:10:27,760 --> 01:10:33,520
regardless of the category, with something that 
doesn't have a level of boldness or intensity.
 

664
01:10:33,520 --> 01:10:39,120
That was an amazing story. Just again, so 
kind of a tip here is if half of your team or,  

665
01:10:39,120 --> 01:10:41,920
I don't know, some percent of your 
team hates it, some percent of your  

666
01:10:41,920 --> 01:10:45,600
team loves it, that's a good sign.
Yeah, it is. It is. Look for that  

667
01:10:45,600 --> 01:10:50,480
polarization. That's what we look for.
I also love this tip of asking people if,  

668
01:10:50,480 --> 01:10:54,800
"Hey, our competitor just launched. They're 
called Windsurf." How your team reacts? If  

669
01:10:54,800 --> 01:10:58,880
they're just like, "Oh, wow, that's a great name. 
I'm interested in that product." That's what you  

670
01:10:58,880 --> 01:11:00,960
want to look for?
Yes, exactly.
 

671
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:07,040
How important is the .com for the name you 
come up with? I imagine it's really hard to  

672
01:11:07,040 --> 01:11:10,720
get these days. Just what do you think about 
domain name when you think about naming?
 

673
01:11:10,720 --> 01:11:16,720
I am so glad you asked this question because 
at this point, it doesn't really matter at  

674
01:11:16,720 --> 01:11:25,760
all. The .com or URL address has become an 
area code. And whether you're in 415 or 615,  

675
01:11:25,760 --> 01:11:35,200
it doesn't really matter to people. And now with 
AI, SEO is going to be less important. And so,  

676
01:11:35,200 --> 01:11:41,680
I just think the principle in play here is you 
got to get the right name first. And then if  

677
01:11:41,680 --> 01:11:48,720
you can get the .com, sure, go ahead. But if 
you can't, there's ways around that. You can  

678
01:11:48,720 --> 01:11:55,360
put a prefix in front of it or a little word 
in front of it or after it, or you go to .ai  

679
01:11:55,360 --> 01:12:02,800
or something like that. But the principle 
in play is let's get the right name first.
 

680
01:12:02,800 --> 01:12:08,640
For those who really... And there are 
people who really get hung up on the .com,  

681
01:12:10,080 --> 01:12:17,360
they tend to older by, the way. And have, in 
their mind, sort of the hotness of the internet  

682
01:12:17,360 --> 01:12:23,680
and having a .com, which did make a difference 
25 years ago. But it's 25 years now or 30,  

683
01:12:23,680 --> 01:12:31,840
right? The good news is because they're less 
valuable, you can typically buy a URL if you  

684
01:12:31,840 --> 01:12:39,280
negotiate the right way and have time for 15, 20, 
25, $30,000. And we say, "Hey, if you can do that,  

685
01:12:39,280 --> 01:12:45,360
have fun. I'd put the $30,000 into market."
Awesome. That's reassuring. I imagine many  

686
01:12:45,360 --> 01:12:48,640
founders are just like, "God dammit, 
there's no names available anymore."  

687
01:12:49,520 --> 01:12:56,320
Let me zoom out and just ask you this question as 
a, maybe, a closing thought to our conversation.
 

688
01:12:56,320 --> 01:12:59,760
Say you were just in an elevator ride with 
someone, and I'm sure this happens to you  

689
01:12:59,760 --> 01:13:04,320
of just like, "Hey, David, I got to come up with 
that name. What's your biggest tip for coming up  

690
01:13:04,320 --> 01:13:08,960
with a great name?" What would your answer be?
I'd go back to forget about the word, think about  

691
01:13:08,960 --> 01:13:18,400
behavior and experience. And then the second thing 
from just a creative help, I'm a big believer in  

692
01:13:18,400 --> 01:13:24,160
synchronicity. And we try to force synchronicity 
here, and I'll give you a couple examples of  

693
01:13:24,160 --> 01:13:31,600
that. But this idea of connecting dots, two 
unrelated ideas together. And so I'll say, "Look,  

694
01:13:31,600 --> 01:13:42,160
if someone says we make sailboats and I'm trying 
to..." I'm here in Sausalito. I guess, that's why  

695
01:13:42,160 --> 01:13:49,360
I thought about that. And I am trying to create 
a new name for my company that builds sailboats.
 

696
01:13:49,360 --> 01:13:57,840
I would say forget about sailboats. I would 
go and pick out some magazines about hunting  

697
01:13:57,840 --> 01:14:07,040
or flying magazines. And I would just look through 
those, get a notepad out, and put out words that  

698
01:14:07,040 --> 01:14:14,000
you like. Things, expressions that you like. And 
then that synchronicity, I said, "I would bet you  

699
01:14:14,000 --> 01:14:20,640
$5 that out of those two magazines, you will 
get a word that you never would've thought of,  

700
01:14:20,640 --> 01:14:28,480
but somehow it would relate to sailing."
That connects very much to your story of  

701
01:14:28,480 --> 01:14:31,200
how you have these different teams, and 
the teams that end up coming up with a  

702
01:14:31,200 --> 01:14:35,200
winning name are the ones thinking about a 
very different version of that product.

